In 2013, the Honduran Congress passed a law that criminalized abortion in all cases, including rape, incest, and when the mother’s life is in danger. The law also criminalizes the provision of abortion services, including the provision of emergency contraception. The law has been used to prosecute women and health care providers for abortion-related offenses.

In 2015, the Inter-American Court of Human Rights ruled that the Honduran law violated the rights of women and girls to life, health, and personal integrity. The court ordered the Honduran government to take steps to ensure that women and girls have access to safe and legal abortion services. The Honduran government has not complied with the court’s order.
